1 Rationale

The aim of this analysis is to check whether samples can be compared across seasons, i.e. if the amount of mRNA identified is constant throughout the year; to ensure that the normalisation does not introduce an artefactual mRNA abundance bias

samples <- read.csv("~/Git/UPSCb/projects/spruce-wood-time-series/doc/samplesmod.csv")
samples <- samples[order(samples$Tissue,samples$Sampling),]

Get the months

months <- substr(samples$Date,1,3)
months[samples$Tissue=="Phloem"][duplicated(months[samples$Tissue=="Phloem"])] <- ""
months[samples$Tissue=="Xylem"][duplicated(months[samples$Tissue=="Xylem"])] <- ""

Identify the winter samples

winterPos <- reduce(IRanges(start=grep("Oct|Nov|Dec|Jan|Feb",samples$Date),width=1))
tissuePos <- which(samples$Tissue=="Xylem")[1] - 0.5

Sort the data

vst <- vst[,match(samples$Filename,colnames(vst))]

sel <- featureSelect(vst,conditions = factor(sprintf("%s%02d",samples$Tissue,samples$Sampling)),
                     exp=5,nrep=2)

3.4 Expression Bins

3.4.1 Expression levels

The expression values are split into 10 bins (i.e. the range min expression - max expression, divided into 10 equivalently sized bins)

bins <- apply(vst[sel,],2,function(co){split(co,cut(co,10))})
dev.null <- sapply(1:10,function(i){
  boxplot(lapply(bins,"[[",i),las=2,
          names=months,
  main=sprintf("expression bin %d%% - %d%%",(i-1)*10,i*10),
  xlab="",ylab="approx. log2 expression")
  abline(v=tissuePos,col=2)})

3.4.2 Number of genes per bins

bSize <- sapply(bins,function(b){sapply(b,length)})
#barplot(bSize,beside = TRUE)

The colors got from red to yellow to blue - across all (0-10% to 90-100%) bins

It is interesting to see that there are more genes contributing to low expression bins and conversely less genes contributing to higher expression in the winter months Also here it is more apparent that the effect in the xylem is less pronounced than in the phloem. There is also an early season effect, which is probably related to wood development.

plot(0,0,xlim=c(1,ncol(bSize)),ylim=range(bSize),type="n",xaxt="n",
     ylab="number of genes",xlab="Months",main="Number of genes per bins")
axis(1,tick = FALSE,labels=months,at=1:ncol(bSize),las=2)
abline(v=tissuePos,col=2)
dev.null <- sapply(1:nrow(bSize),function(i){lines(bSize[i,],col=cols[i],lwd=2)})

plot(1,1,xlim=c(1,ncol(bSize)),ylim=range(bSize),type="n",xaxt="n",
     ylab="number of genes",xlab="Months",log="y",main="Number of genes per bins")
axis(1,tick = FALSE,labels=months,at=1:ncol(bSize),las=2)

3.4.3 Fold change variation within bins

dat <- sapply(1:10,function(i){diff(range(sapply(lapply(bins,"[[",i),median)))})
p.dat <- sapply(1:10,function(i){diff(range(sapply(lapply(bins[samples$Tissue == "Phloem"],"[[",i),median)))})
x.dat <- sapply(1:10,function(i){diff(range(sapply(lapply(bins[samples$Tissue == "Xylem"],"[[",i),median)))})

plot(dat,main="Fold change per bin",ylab="fold change",xlab="bins (0-10% to 90-100%)",
     col=1,pch=19)
points(p.dat,col=pal[1],pch=19)
points(x.dat,col=pal[2],pch=19)
legend("topleft",bty="n",pch=19,col=c(1,pal[1:2]),c("all","phloem","xylem"))

3.4.3.1 More conservatively (avoiding a few outliers)

dat <- sapply(1:10,function(i){median(sapply(lapply(bins,"[[",i),median)[unlist(winterPos)]) - 
    median(sapply(lapply(bins,"[[",i),median)[-unlist(winterPos)])})
p.dat <- sapply(1:10,function(i){
  median(sapply(lapply(bins[samples$Tissue == "Phloem"],"[[",i),median)[unlist(winterPos[1,])]) - 
    median(sapply(lapply(bins[samples$Tissue == "Phloem"],"[[",i),median)[-unlist(winterPos[1,])])})
  
x.dat <- sapply(1:10,function(i){
  median(sapply(lapply(bins[samples$Tissue == "Xylem"],"[[",i),median)[unlist(winterPos[2,]) - round(tissuePos)]) - 
    median(sapply(lapply(bins[samples$Tissue == "Xylem"],"[[",i),median)[-unlist(winterPos[2,]) - round(tissuePos)])})

plot(dat,main="Fold change per bin",ylab="fold change",xlab="bins (0-10% to 90-100%)",
     col=1,pch=19,ylim=range(c(dat,p.dat,x.dat)))
points(p.dat,col=pal[1],pch=19)
points(x.dat,col=pal[2],pch=19)
legend("topleft",bty="n",pch=19,col=c(1,pal[1:2]),c("all","phloem","xylem"))

4 Conclusion

There is a clear variation across the season in the number of genes expressed or in the level of expression of the genes. The drop in the number of expressed genes and the corresponding increase in the expression of these genes does correlate with the winter months (Oct-Feb). The binning of expression shows that this pattern affect all ranges of expression. However, the number of genes affected is also varying across the expression bins, with more lowly expressed genes and less highly expressed genes contributing to the expression across the winter. Whether this is biological or technical is challenging. The fact that the winter-increase in expression is fairly constant per bin and does not increase a 1.8 fold allows for the safe selection of winter-specific genes, provided they have a fold-change > 1.8 with other seasons.
